[Student "S"]
{North is to play 4\H. East leads the \CJ. West wins \C A K Q then switches to a trump.

West takes \C A K Q then switches to a trump.

You must win the next 10 tricks but you only have 9 winners.

West opened 1NT, showing 15-17 points, and East has already produced 2 Jacks. So both the \SQ and \DK are with West and you will have to put the squeeze on him. 

You are in dummy, having won their trump exit with the \HK.

Since you need all the tricks the count is already rectified.

You plan to squeeze West by running the long \Hs in your hand, but the problem is that the \DQ is not a Threat card yet. To make it a Threat you need to unblock dummy's \DA. So play the \DA, then pull trumps with the \H A Q. 

Unblocking the \DA to make your \DQ a squeeze Threat is called the Vienna Coup.

With 6 cards left to be played you are ready to apply pressure to West.

Play the \H 9 8, discarding \Ds from dummy. West is not troubled yet, he can discard the \DJ and the \S3. 

[showcards N:SA,SK,SJ,D6 E:SQ,ST,S9,DK S:S8,S7,H6,DQ W:S6,S5,D9,D8]

West is now looking a little nervous, like he has a big target on his back!

Play the \H6 and throw dummy's \D6.

West can choose his fate. If he throws the \S9 you will know that his \SQ will drop since his third card <b>MUST</b> be the \DK. So you would just play to the high \Ss and the \SJ would be good.

Or, he can throw his \DK which makes your \DQ a winner. 

That worked great, right? Let's back up and pretend you had NOT unblocked the \DA. We will just add one \D to everybody's hand and look at the ending.

Now when you play your \H6 as a squeeze card you have a problem. You are squeezing dummy, not West.

If you discard the \D6 West will throw his \DJ, then sit back and wait for his \SQ trick.

But if you discard dummy's \SJ instead, West will match that by throwing his \S9, then sit back and wait for his \DK trick.

Only by visualizing the ending and using the Vienna Coup can this hand be made.}
[Play "W"]CJ

